<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1437,150,574]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,446,150,177]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Biology and habitat.</emphasis>
The hostplant is 
<taxonomicName authority="Fingerhuth" authorityName="Fingerhuth" box="[649,996,151,177]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Rumex" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polygonales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thyrsiflorus">
<emphasis box="[649,864,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Rumex thyrsiflorus</emphasis>
Fingerhuth
</taxonomicName>
(our own observations); adults are on the wing in May and June and fly in the immediate vicinity of this plant. We also observed oviposition and reared several specimens from this plant. Typical habitats are meadows and pastures, but often also anthropogenic places such as roadsides, parks and graveyards. This species is highly endangered by overgrazing of most habitats in the small distribution area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
